    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 22 @ 2021/2022",
    "Question": {
      "content": "The phenomenon whereby a charge appears on an initially uncharged conductor due to close proximity is known as",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "electrostatic induction",
        "electrostatic induction",
        "current",
        "voltage"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "electrostatic induction"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "The phenomenon where a charge appears on an initially uncharged conductor due to the proximity of a charged object is called electrostatic induction, which is why electrostatic induction is the correct answer (noting the options list it twice). This occurs because the nearby charge induces a separation of charges in the conductor. Current refers to the flow of charge, not the induction process. Voltage is the potential difference, not the phenomenon described."
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electrostatic Induction",
      "Electrostatics",
      "Conductors",
      "Electric Fields"
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 4 @ 2018/2019",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A charged insulator and an uncharged conductor",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "always repel each other",
        "always attract each other",
        "exert no electrostatic force on each other",
        "may attract or repel depending on whether the charge is positive or negative"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "always attract each other"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<p>An uncharged conductor develops <b>induced charges</b> when near a charged insulator due to electrostatic induction. Here’s why attraction occurs:</p> <ol> <li><b>Polarization</b>: The charged insulator (+Q or -Q) repels like charges in the conductor and attracts opposite charges. For example: <ul> <li>If the insulator is <i>positively charged</i>, electrons in the conductor move toward it, leaving a net positive charge on the far side.</li> <li>The <b>attractive force</b> between +Q and the nearby induced -q is stronger than the <b>repulsive force</b> between +Q and the distant +q (since distance affects Coulomb’s Law: \\[ F = \\frac{k q_1 q_2}{r^2} \\]).</li> </ul></li> <li><b>Net Force</b>: The conductor experiences a net attraction regardless of the insulator’s charge sign. This is because the induced opposite charge is always closer to the insulator.</li> </ol> <p>Thus, <b>always attract each other</b> is correct.</p>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electromagnetism",
      "Coulomb's Law",
      "Electric Field",
      "Electrostatic Induction"
    ]
  }
